01:28:23.881 --> 01:28:27.175
OK. I'll cancel my agent appointment.

1430
01:28:27.260 --> 01:28:28.927
It's good. This is good.

1431
01:28:29.053 --> 01:28:31.805
I'll see you soon. Bye.

1432
01:28:31.931 --> 01:28:34.308
- Was it him?
- Yeah.

1433
01:28:36.811 --> 01:28:39.896
So, you'll have to be prepared
to cash flow the first six months.

1434
01:28:39.939 --> 01:28:42.149
Is that right, Chris? A half year?

1435
01:28:42.191 --> 01:28:43.191
Yes.

1436
01:28:43.276 --> 01:28:45.902
A half year should do it, maybe less.

1437
01:28:45.945 --> 01:28:48.655
Good. Jolly good.
Well, see you next time.

1438
01:28:55.038 --> 01:28:56.788
Good.

1439
01:28:58.082 --> 01:29:00.959
Sayonara indeed. I thought you
showed some interesting ideas there

1440
01:29:01.085 --> 01:29:03.170
for developing their capacity.

1441
01:29:03.212 --> 01:29:05.714
- I'm excited about this venture, Rod.
- Good, good.

1442
01:29:15.600 --> 01:29:18.602
- Playing a little tennis later?
- Yes.

1443
01:29:19.604 --> 01:29:23.106
Amazing energy. Love it. Envy it.

1444
01:30:29.674 --> 01:30:32.801
- Yes?
- Hello. I'm Chris.

1445
01:30:32.927 --> 01:30:35.554
I'm a friend of Nola's,
your neighbor from next door.

1446
01:30:35.638 --> 01:30:36.805
We met here last...

1447
01:30:36.931 --> 01:30:39.307
I'm sorry, I don't let anybody in.

1448
01:30:39.392 --> 01:30:41.393
But... but, do you not remember?
We met...

1449
01:30:42.812 --> 01:30:46.022
She asked you something
about your trouble with your mice,

1450
01:30:46.065 --> 01:30:48.692
and you mentioned
something about peanut butter.

1451
01:30:48.776 --> 01:30:51.778
- Oh, yes. Yes.
- Yes.

1452
01:30:53.698 --> 01:30:55.699
I'm Chris Wilton, the tennis instructor.

1453
01:30:55.825 --> 01:30:57.200
Well, what's the trouble?

1454
01:30:57.285 --> 01:31:00.078
No trouble at all really, and I...
I don't mean to disturb you.

1455
01:31:00.204 --> 01:31:04.082
I was wondering if I could...
could look at your TV reception.

1456
01:31:04.208 --> 01:31:07.711
- We seem to have trouble next door.
- Oh, with the TV?

1457
01:31:07.712 --> 01:31:08.795
Yes.

1458
01:31:08.838 --> 01:31:12.841
We're getting some interference,
and it's Nola's favorite TV night.

1459
01:31:12.925 --> 01:31:16.094
So I don't know if it's the
aerial on the roof or if it's us.

1460
01:31:16.179 --> 01:31:18.180
- It's in there.
- Thank... thank you.

1461
01:31:18.222 --> 01:31:20.223
I have to take my medicine.

1462
01:31:36.491 --> 01:31:40.243
There was no trouble before.
I had it on and it was fine.

1463
01:32:03.267 --> 01:32:06.269
Didn't you say your name was Harris?

1464
01:35:48.701 --> 01:35:50.702
Mrs. Eastby?

1465
01:35:53.873 --> 01:35:55.832
It's lan.

1466
01:36:03.007 --> 01:36:04.883
Mrs. Eastby?

1467
01:36:09.638 --> 01:36:11.848
Mrs. Eastby? It's lan.

1468
01:36:14.143 --> 01:36:17.604
I'm going down the corner shop.
Can I get you anything?

1469
01:36:21.901 --> 01:36:24.611
Mrs. Eastby, are you all right?

1470
01:36:48.427 --> 01:36:49.427
- Hi, princess.
- Hi.

1471
01:36:49.553 --> 01:36:52.180
D'you ever get that
portable CD player we talked about?

1472
01:36:52.264 --> 01:36:54.307
Yes, I did.
Thank you so much for helping me.

1473
01:36:54.433 --> 01:36:55.391
Excellent.

1474
01:37:12.326 --> 01:37:14.828
- See you later. Bye-bye.
- OK. Bye.

1475
01:37:45.442 --> 01:37:46.734
Nola.

1476
01:37:57.121 --> 01:37:58.580
Excuse me.

1477
01:38:08.007 --> 01:38:09.507
Hello.

1478
01:38:10.259 --> 01:38:11.593
Where are you?

1479
01:38:12.761 --> 01:38:15.346
I'm almost there. I'll be two minutes.

1480
01:38:47.046 --> 01:38:48.504
- Good evening.
- Hello.

1481
01:38:53.552 --> 01:38:55.553
- How much?
- That's two pounds, please.

1482
01:38:55.679 --> 01:38:57.180
Two pounds.

1483
01:39:02.311 --> 01:39:04.312
- Two pounds. My tickets?
- Yes. Thank you.

1484
01:39:21.705 --> 01:39:23.331
It's a terrible mess in there, sir.

1485
01:39:23.415 --> 01:39:25.458
Well, I think it's pretty obvious
what's happened here.

1486
01:39:25.542 --> 01:39:27.543
Someone's robbed
and killed the old lady.

1487
01:39:27.586 --> 01:39:28.920
As he, or they, were running out

1488
01:39:28.963 --> 01:39:31.464
they've run into the Rice woman
coming in, so they've shot her too.

1489
01:39:31.590 --> 01:39:32.840
Either out of panic,

1490
01:39:32.925 --> 01:39:35.927
or because they saw a chance
to make an additional score.

1491
01:39:35.970 --> 01:39:38.596
Poor unsuspecting soul
came home at the wrong moment.

1492
01:39:38.681 --> 01:39:40.807
He's cleared out the house
of all prescription drugs, sir.

1493
01:39:40.849 --> 01:39:43.226
Oh, no, it's definitely
a drugs-related robbery.

1494
01:39:43.310 --> 01:39:45.687
He might have known there
was an old lady living in flat 8.

1495
01:39:45.729 --> 01:39:47.105
Probably cased her.

1496
01:39:47.106 --> 01:39:49.482
Was surprised by running
into the other woman.

1497
01:39:49.608 --> 01:39:51.609
She picked the wrong time to come home.

1498
01:39:52.111 --> 01:39:54.320
Some people just don't have any luck.

1499
01:39:55.823 --> 01:39:58.324
Yeah, I just spoke to her.
This is unbelievable.

1500
01:39:58.367 --> 01:40:00.243
Half an hour ago I came down the stairs,

1501
01:40:00.369 --> 01:40:01.995
knocked on Mrs. Eastby's door
'cause I couldn't...

1502
01:40:02.079 --> 01:40:03.246
Do you need anything from the car?

1503
01:40:03.330 --> 01:40:05.373
Yeah. You can tell the
exhibits officer to get a move on,

1504
01:40:05.457 --> 01:40:08.710
- 'cause this is getting ridiculous.
- Yeah, this is quite important.

1505
01:40:08.752 --> 01:40:10.628
She usually bakes today, and
I thought maybe she'd run out of stuff.

1506
01:40:10.754 --> 01:40:12.463
So I asked her if she
needed anything, and then

1507
01:40:12.506 --> 01:40:13.881
- So, half an hour ago? Spoke to her?
- she didn't answer.

1508
01:40:13.966 --> 01:40:16.718
- Yeah, half an hour ago. Yeah.
- So whoever it was, was still in there.

1509
01:40:16.760 --> 01:40:18.511
That's terrifying. I can't believe that.

1510
01:40:18.595 --> 01:40:21.222
- So someone was in there...?
- And you spoke to Nola Rice,

1511
01:40:21.265 --> 01:40:23.266
- and did she say anything?
- Sorry to interrupt.

1512
01:40:23.267 --> 01:40:25.018
Could we send the
photographers in now, please?

1513
01:40:25.144 --> 01:40:26.269
No, hang on. If you just wait.

1514
01:40:26.270 --> 01:40:28.646
We've just got to get the
exhibit officer in there first.

1515
01:40:28.772 --> 01:40:32.025
Chris, Chris, can you
liaise with this man here?

1516
01:40:32.109 --> 01:40:34.610
Wait, wait, wait, wait.
Just catch him there.

1517
01:40:34.653 --> 01:40:37.030
Well, I ran...
Yeah, I bumped into Nola right here...

1518
01:40:37.156 --> 01:40:38.990
Scenes of Crime will be
on their way very shortly, all right?

1519
01:40:39.033 --> 01:40:40.366
- Yeah...
- Yeah, I spoke...

1520
01:40:40.409 --> 01:40:42.618
I bumped into her here.
We talked and we chatted.

1521
01:40:42.661 --> 01:40:44.537
I recommended a piece
of music equipment.

1522
01:40:44.663 --> 01:40:47.040
- She'd bought it. Yeah, and...
- Music equipment? What was that?

1523
01:40:47.166 --> 01:40:50.501
Nothing. It was a portable CD player
which reads MP3s, CD rewrites...

1524
01:40:50.544 --> 01:40:52.545
It's drugs, guv.
Someone after money for some drugs.

1525
01:40:52.671 --> 01:40:54.756
Well, Mrs. Eastby wasn't wealthy.

1526
01:40:54.798 --> 01:40:56.049
- They don't care.
- Drugs?

1527
01:40:56.175 --> 01:40:59.010
Yeah, definitely drugs.
Someone after money for 'em, and...

1528
01:40:59.053 --> 01:41:01.179
They'll kill you for a pound
if they wanted to, you know.

1529
01:41:01.263 --> 01:41:02.680
Well, it's a sorry state of affairs,
isn't it?

1530
01:41:02.681 --> 01:41:06.059
Well, it's not as if the old lady
had any enemies. She rarely went out.

1531
01:41:06.185 --> 01:41:07.435
- Used a shotgun.
- A shotgun?

1532
01:41:07.519 --> 01:41:09.187
That's a... That's a bit obvious,
isn't it?

1533
01:41:09.313 --> 01:41:11.397
- Somebody must've seen something.
- Oh, not if it was sawn-off.

1534
01:41:11.440 --> 01:41:14.442
They can make them pretty small.
Catherine, love, you can't park there.

1535
01:41:14.526 --> 01:41:16.694
Leave that clear.
We've got the SOCO coming down.

1536
01:41:18.530 --> 01:41:20.782
Did you like the musical last night?

1537
01:41:21.450 --> 01:41:25.411
Yeah, I did. It was good fun.
Pretty music.

1538
01:41:25.454 --> 01:41:27.830
Yeah, he's very good.

1539
01:41:28.540 --> 01:41:30.666
I'm gonna get tickets
for Mummy and Papa.

1540
01:41:30.709 --> 01:41:32.794
Good.

1541
01:41:35.547 --> 01:41:38.966
- Oh, my God.
- What? What is it?

1542
01:41:40.344 --> 01:41:43.346
Oh, my God! Nola!

1543
01:41:43.347 --> 01:41:46.182
- Nola Rice.
- What?

1544
01:41:46.475 --> 01:41:50.186
She was killed in a burglary.
A... a drugs burglary.

1545
01:41:50.813 --> 01:41:53.815
What? Here, let me see that.

1546
01:41:53.857 --> 01:41:55.691
Jesus Christ!

1547
01:41:59.613 --> 01:42:01.697
Apparently, she was
coming home from work,

1548
01:42:01.740 --> 01:42:05.743
and someone who was already there
who'd burgled another flat and rob...

1549
01:42:05.828 --> 01:42:08.329
And shot an old lady,
ran into Nola by chance, and...

1550
01:42:08.372 --> 01:42:12.375
She was entering the building,
and he was running out and he shot her.

1551
01:42:12.459 --> 01:42:14.752
Oh, my God.

1552
01:42:20.259 --> 01:42:21.843
Hello?

1553
01:42:22.761 --> 01:42:25.388
Yeah. Yeah,
we've just this second read it.

1554
01:42:25.514 --> 01:42:27.098
Isn't it just terrible?

1555
01:42:27.141 --> 01:42:30.393
I never got along with her,
but this is just tragic.

1556
01:42:30.519 --> 01:42:33.521
- It's tragic.
- Does Tom know?

1557
01:42:33.647 --> 01:42:35.773
I've just called him.
He can't believe it.

1558
01:42:36.400 --> 01:42:38.109
I know.

1559
01:42:38.152 --> 01:42:40.736
Wait, wait, that must be him.
I'll call you back.

1560
01:42:40.779 --> 01:42:42.530
Hello?

1561
01:42:42.614 --> 01:42:45.116
Yeah, we've just read it,
and Mummy just called.

1562
01:42:45.159 --> 01:42:48.035
Well, yeah, yeah, I know.
I mean, wrong place at the wrong time.

1563
01:42:48.120 --> 01:42:49.495
I suppose she must've...

1564
01:42:49.538 --> 01:42:52.248
I mean, disturbed a burglar
or burglars, or whatever.

1565
01:42:52.291 --> 01:42:54.542
I mean, it doesn't... It doesn't say
how many of them there were.

1566
01:42:54.626 --> 01:42:56.377
Well, even Mummy's really shaken up,

1567
01:42:56.420 --> 01:42:58.629
and you know they
weren't exactly friends.

1568
01:42:58.672 --> 01:43:01.924
It says here that there's been a rise
in drug-related crime in the area

1569
01:43:02.050 --> 01:43:03.926
over the past year.

1570
01:43:04.011 --> 01:43:06.637
Did you hear that? Yeah.

1571
01:43:06.680 --> 01:43:11.058
I just can't believe it.
It's just... I know.

1572
01:43:17.441 --> 01:43:18.816
Mummy.

1573
01:43:20.944 --> 01:43:22.945
I've got something to tell you.

1574
01:43:23.030 --> 01:43:25.072
But I want Chris to be here.

1575
01:43:26.325 --> 01:43:28.201
Chris?

1576
01:43:28.327 --> 01:43:31.287
- Where'd he go?
- I don't know.

1577
01:43:31.330 --> 01:43:33.331
He was just in here. Chris?

1578
01:43:34.041 --> 01:43:36.042
Chris?

1579
01:43:43.342 --> 01:43:44.717
He was just here.

1580
01:43:44.801 --> 01:43:46.469
Well, what did you want to tell me?

1581
01:43:46.470 --> 01:43:48.971
Just wait. Wait, wait. Chris?

1582
01:44:21.338 --> 01:44:23.506
Where are you? Chris?

1583
01:44:25.008 --> 01:44:26.259
Well, what did you want to tell me?

1584
01:44:26.343 --> 01:44:28.010
Well, I just really want him to be here.

1585
01:44:28.095 --> 01:44:30.388
Hang on, there he is. There you are!

1586
01:44:30.973 --> 01:44:33.099
- Can we tell her now?
- Sure.

1587
01:44:33.141 --> 01:44:35.393
Well, I wanted you to be here.

1588
01:44:35.477 --> 01:44:37.019
Well, what is it?

1589
01:44:37.104 --> 01:44:38.521
Mummy...

1590
01:44:38.647 --> 01:44:41.399
You can finally
crack open the champagne.

1591
01:44:41.483 --> 01:44:43.150
It looks like I'm pregnant.

1592
01:44:43.277 --> 01:44:45.528
- When did you hear?
- This morning.

1593
01:44:45.612 --> 01:44:49.407
- Oh, I'm so delighted.
- Oh, good.

1594
01:44:50.033 --> 01:44:51.534
Alec?

1595
01:44:51.618 --> 01:44:54.287
Alec? Come here.

1596
01:44:54.538 --> 01:44:56.914
We're both walking on air.

1597
01:44:57.040 --> 01:45:00.167
Well, you're walking on air. Your
husband looks a bit shell shocked.

1598
01:45:00.252 --> 01:45:02.128
- 'Cause I've exhausted him, poor thing.
- What?

1599
01:45:02.170 --> 01:45:03.421
Chloe's pregnant.

1600
01:45:03.547 --> 01:45:06.007
Oh, what a great day.
Oh, my darling, congratulations.

1601
01:45:06.049 --> 01:45:08.426
I'm absolutely thrilled.
I couldn't be more pleased.

1602
01:45:08.552 --> 01:45:10.177
Thank you so much.
It's such a relief.

1603
01:45:10.262 --> 01:45:11.178
Excuse me, sir. Excuse me.

1604
01:45:11.305 --> 01:45:12.805
- Yes?
- Phone call, sir. Your secretary.

1605
01:45:12.931 --> 01:45:15.266
It's wonderful, isn't it? Look at her,
doesn't she look gorgeous?

1606
01:45:15.309 --> 01:45:19.145
- Margaret, I'm pregnant!
- Congratulations! That's wonderful.

1607
01:45:19.187 --> 01:45:20.646
Thank you, Margaret.

1608
01:45:21.565 --> 01:45:23.065
Sam?

1609
01:45:23.066 --> 01:45:25.693
Yeah, there's a message for you
that a Mike Banner,

1610
01:45:25.777 --> 01:45:27.653
Detective Mike Banner, called.

1611
01:45:27.696 --> 01:45:30.823
He wants you to call him
at Shepherd's Bush police station.

1612
01:45:31.325 --> 01:45:34.410
Yeah. No, I don't think it's urgent,
but he left a number.

1613
01:45:34.453 --> 01:45:36.412
- Banner?
- Sweetheart...

1614
01:45:36.455 --> 01:45:37.830
I bet it was that night...

1615
01:45:37.956 --> 01:45:41.208
- You better give me the number.
- Look, that's flattering.

1616
01:45:43.712 --> 01:45:47.173
Well, the last time you went,
he said everything was fine, didn't he?

1617
01:45:47.215 --> 01:45:49.425
Yes, and he just made me
completely calm down.

1618
01:45:49.468 --> 01:45:51.677
Oh, I just can't believe it.
It's marvelous.

1619
01:45:51.720 --> 01:45:53.346
OK. Thanks, Samantha. Bye.

1620
01:45:53.430 --> 01:45:55.973
He just seemed odd,
there was something weird.

1621
01:45:58.101 --> 01:46:01.228
- Granny would have been thrilled.
- ...alternative medicine.

1622
01:46:01.355 --> 01:46:04.482
Granny would have loved it.
I wish she could be here.

1623
01:46:04.608 --> 01:46:07.443
- Thank God. Thank God.
- Congratulations!

1624
01:46:07.486 --> 01:46:09.236
Detective Banner, please.

1625
01:46:09.321 --> 01:46:11.322
This is Chris Wilton.

1626
01:46:14.993 --> 01:46:15.993
Oh, hello.

1627
01:46:16.078 --> 01:46:18.579
This is Chris Wilton. You called?

1628
01:46:18.622 --> 01:46:21.499
Oh, yes. I was wondering if there
was a time you could drop in here?

1629
01:46:21.625 --> 01:46:23.834
Or if it's more convenient,
we can come and see you.

1630
01:46:23.877 --> 01:46:27.338
- In reference to what?
- I'd rather not explain on the phone.

1631
01:46:27.381 --> 01:46:30.633
It's just a few questions, and I'm sure
you'd prefer it to be discreet.

1632
01:46:33.512 --> 01:46:35.763
I've no reason to bring a lawyer, do I?

1633
01:46:35.847 --> 01:46:37.848
I certainly hope not.

1634
01:47:44.416 --> 01:47:46.959
- Chris Wilton. Detective Banner.
- Good afternoon.

1635
01:47:47.085 --> 01:47:50.045
- How do you do? Take a seat.
- Thank you.

1636
01:47:50.964 --> 01:47:52.965
This is nothing to be alarmed about.

1637
01:47:53.049 --> 01:47:57.094
We're just doing a routine investigation
into the Betty Eastby-Nola Rice murders.

1638
01:47:58.722 --> 01:48:01.348
Were you acquainted
with either of the victims?

1639
01:48:01.475 --> 01:48:03.851
Peripherally, I knew Nola Rice.

1640
01:48:04.436 --> 01:48:05.728
How?

1641
01:48:06.605 --> 01:48:09.857
She was engaged for a time
to the man who's now my brother-in-law.

1642
01:48:09.941 --> 01:48:11.692
That's...

1643
01:48:12.360 --> 01:48:14.487
- ...Tom Hewett?
- That's correct.

1644
01:48:16.323 --> 01:48:19.575
They broke up. A year ago. More.

1645
01:48:20.994 --> 01:48:22.995
When did you last see her?

1646
01:48:23.955 --> 01:48:26.248
Oh, God, I can't remember.

1647
01:48:29.711 --> 01:48:32.880
At the Tate Modern.
My wife and I ran into her.

1648
01:48:33.006 --> 01:48:35.466
But that was a long time ago.

1649
01:48:37.260 --> 01:48:38.886
Have you seen her since?

1650
01:48:39.346 --> 01:48:41.138
Not that I recall.

1651
01:48:43.892 --> 01:48:45.518
Have...?

1652
01:48:46.728 --> 01:48:48.145
Have you ever seen this?

1653
01:48:49.147 --> 01:48:51.148
No. What is it?

1654
01:48:52.484 --> 01:48:55.027
Are you aware
that Nola Rice kept a diary?

1655
01:49:04.538 --> 01:49:06.247
No.

1656
01:49:07.249 --> 01:49:09.250
As you can see...

1657
01:49:09.793 --> 01:49:12.253
...you're all over it.

1658
01:49:19.511 --> 01:49:21.804
Yes, I can see that.

1659
01:49:25.058 --> 01:49:27.309
Do you still claim
that you haven't seen her,

1660
01:49:27.310 --> 01:49:29.895
except for more than a year ago
at the Tate Modern?

1661
01:49:32.941 --> 01:49:36.443
You can't blame me for trying to hide
the fact that I had an affair with her.

1662
01:49:37.153 --> 01:49:39.446
But you people have to protect me here.

1663
01:49:40.407 --> 01:49:43.200
I hope you don't think
I had anything to do with her murder.

1664
01:49:43.285 --> 01:49:45.286
How long did your affair go on?

1665
01:49:50.458 --> 01:49:53.335
It began casually
when she was still engaged to Tom.

1666
01:49:54.170 --> 01:49:56.338
They broke up, she moved away.

1667
01:49:57.340 --> 01:50:01.176
She came back and I ran into her
at the Tate Modern, and it began again.

1668
01:50:03.597 --> 01:50:05.598
God, have a heart.

1669
01:50:06.349 --> 01:50:08.726
My wife is gonna have a baby.

1670
01:50:09.060 --> 01:50:11.312
This will devastate her.

1671
01:50:12.480 --> 01:50:13.856
Did you...

1672
01:50:14.232 --> 01:50:18.110
...promise that you were going
to leave your wife and marry Miss Rice?

1673
01:50:18.486 --> 01:50:20.613
No, I did not.

1674
01:50:20.989 --> 01:50:23.324
I mean, it's possible
she had that fantasy.

1675
01:50:24.242 --> 01:50:27.578
And, obviously, she wrote that I did.

1676
01:50:33.001 --> 01:50:35.711
But I tried to finesse
that point with her.

1677
01:50:35.754 --> 01:50:38.088
I didn't want the
sexual relationship to end,

1678
01:50:38.131 --> 01:50:40.215
but I'm not gonna break up my home.

1679
01:50:41.885 --> 01:50:44.887
My wife and I are
trying very hard to have a baby.

1680
01:50:44.888 --> 01:50:48.599
We've seen several
fertility doctors, et cetera.

1681
01:50:49.643 --> 01:50:53.270
You can check that out if you like,
but I beg you to be discreet.

1682
01:50:53.396 --> 01:50:55.397
But you did lead her on,

1683
01:50:55.482 --> 01:50:58.275
so that she had the impression
you were unhappy at home.

1684
01:50:58.902 --> 01:51:01.278
I tried to tip-toe around it
and not lead her on,

1685
01:51:01.279 --> 01:51:04.031
but she's going to believe
what she wants to believe.

1686
01:51:04.908 --> 01:51:10.412
Look, don't irresponsibly run roughshod
over this and wreck people's lives.

1687
01:51:11.039 --> 01:51:13.916
I mean, there is no case
because I would not harm anyone,

1688
01:51:13.917 --> 01:51:16.043
much less Nola Rice.

1689
01:51:21.424 --> 01:51:24.301
Isn't it obvious
that somebody killed her neighbor,

1690
01:51:24.386 --> 01:51:26.428
and she walked in when it was happening?

1691
01:51:28.306 --> 01:51:31.809
God, I beg you, don't go on
a fishing expedition over this and...

1692
01:51:32.185 --> 01:51:34.186
...wreck people's lives.

1693
01:51:34.312 --> 01:51:37.398
My family, my marriage is at stake.

1694
01:51:38.441 --> 01:51:41.068
We just have to
check out everything in a murder case.

1695
01:51:41.152 --> 01:51:43.570
OK, but I'm not your man.

1696
01:51:44.072 --> 01:51:47.282
I know it's not the most
honorable thing to cheat on your wife,

1697
01:51:47.325 --> 01:51:49.576
but that does not make me a murderer.

1698
01:51:49.786 --> 01:51:52.705
We're... obligated
to review the situation.

1699
01:51:52.789 --> 01:51:54.790
I understand
it's sensitive stuff for you.

1700
01:51:54.833 --> 01:51:56.458
And if we have to talk to you again,

1701
01:51:56.459 --> 01:51:58.836
we'll do everything in our power
to keep it very private.

1702
01:51:58.920 --> 01:52:00.462
Your personal life's your own.

1703
01:52:00.463 --> 01:52:04.341
We're not making any moral judgments,
just investigating a crime.

1704
01:52:14.561 --> 01:52:16.603
I understand.

1705
01:52:17.564 --> 01:52:19.231
Look...

1706
01:52:19.315 --> 01:52:21.483
...if you have to get
in contact with me again,

1707
01:52:21.568 --> 01:52:23.569
which, God in heaven,
I hope you don't,

1708
01:52:23.611 --> 01:52:25.612
please call me on my mobile.

1709
01:52:25.989 --> 01:52:28.115
This is my number.

1710
01:52:29.993 --> 01:52:31.577
Thanks.

1711
01:52:32.245 --> 01:52:33.245
One other thing.

1712
01:52:33.371 --> 01:52:35.748
Do you own or have access to a shotgun?

1713
01:52:37.876 --> 01:52:39.376
Me?

1714
01:52:39.586 --> 01:52:40.753
No.

1715
01:52:40.879 --> 01:52:44.715
My father-in-law shoots
on the estate, but not me.

1716
01:52:44.758 --> 01:52:47.009
You can check it out, but...

1717
01:52:47.969 --> 01:52:51.889
...I beg you to consider mine
and his position.

1718
01:52:52.015 --> 01:52:54.099
Of course.

1719
01:52:57.020 --> 01:52:59.021
Thank you.

1720
01:53:07.655 --> 01:53:09.656
So, what do you think?

1721
01:53:10.241 --> 01:53:12.034
I think it's what it looks like.

1722
01:53:12.035 --> 01:53:14.161
Someone robbed and killed Mrs. Eastby,

1723
01:53:14.245 --> 01:53:17.790
who was surprised leaving,
and killed Nola Rice.

1724
01:53:18.792 --> 01:53:22.377
Yeah, I know. I know, it's got
drug robbery written all over it.

1725
01:53:22.420 --> 01:53:24.421
He's 'specting a baby.

1726
01:53:24.631 --> 01:53:27.049
OK, he's not gonna win
a medal for fidelity, but...

1727
01:53:28.176 --> 01:53:29.802
...we can find out discreetly enough

1728
01:53:29.928 --> 01:53:32.888
whether the Hewetts
had a shotgun unaccounted for.

1729
01:53:34.766 --> 01:53:38.811
I don't think that he would know the
first thing about stealing one though,

1730
01:53:38.937 --> 01:53:41.772
never mind sawing one off.

1731
01:53:42.565 --> 01:53:45.567
It's a bit of a stretch.
He's got no previous convictions.

1732
01:53:45.568 --> 01:53:47.319
Not even a speeding ticket.

1733
01:53:47.445 --> 01:53:50.197
The coroner says
that Eastby was killed first.

1734
01:53:50.281 --> 01:53:52.574
- Yeah.
- There's no sign of a forced entry.

1735
01:53:52.700 --> 01:53:54.910
So Mrs. Eastby knew the killer,
if she let him in.

1736
01:53:54.953 --> 01:53:56.453
Well, come on, Mike.

1737
01:53:56.579 --> 01:53:58.413
Ninety percent
of the crimes we go out on,

1738
01:53:58.456 --> 01:54:00.582
people open their doors
and invite the criminals in.

1739
01:54:00.708 --> 01:54:02.960
Yeah, I know, you're right.
I'm just thinking out loud.

1740
01:54:03.086 --> 01:54:06.088
- It's just he's got a real motive.
- Yeah, maybe.

1741
01:54:06.089 --> 01:54:10.717
But a motive, as you and I
both painfully know, is not a case.

1742
01:54:10.802 --> 01:54:13.846
I'm torn because the Rice murder
was clearly an afterthought,

1743
01:54:13.930 --> 01:54:15.806
but I'd love to pursue it a little more.

1744
01:54:15.849 --> 01:54:19.226
But I'm reluctant to fish around
and cause problems for everybody.

1745
01:54:19.310 --> 01:54:21.603
Well, if something develops,
we can pursue it.

1746
01:54:21.604 --> 01:54:24.356
I doubt anything's
gonna drop into our laps.

1747
01:56:22.100 --> 01:56:23.809
Chris.

1748
01:56:33.736 --> 01:56:35.487
Nola...

1749
01:56:37.615 --> 01:56:39.866
...it wasn't easy.

1750
01:56:40.827 --> 01:56:43.578
But when the time came,
I could pull the trigger.

1751
01:56:45.498 --> 01:56:48.500
You never know who your neighbors are
till there's a crisis.

1752
01:56:50.128 --> 01:56:54.256
You can learn to push the guilt
under the rug and... go on.

1753
01:56:55.466 --> 01:56:57.259
You have to.

1754
01:56:57.260 --> 01:56:59.845
Otherwise it overwhelms you.

1755
01:56:59.887 --> 01:57:02.097
And what about me?

1756
01:57:02.140 --> 01:57:04.891
What about the next-door neighbor?

1757
01:57:05.643 --> 01:57:08.645
I had no involvement
in this awful affair.

1758
01:57:10.106 --> 01:57:14.985
Is there no problem about me
having to die as an innocent bystander?

1759
01:57:16.904 --> 01:57:21.283
The innocent are sometimes slain
to make way for a grander scheme.

1760
01:57:23.411 --> 01:57:25.662
You were collateral damage.

1761
01:57:25.747 --> 01:57:28.165
So was your own child.

1762
01:57:32.420 --> 01:57:34.421
Sophocles said:

1763
01:57:35.923 --> 01:57:38.133
"To never have been born

1764
01:57:38.676 --> 01:57:41.178
may be the greatest boon of all."

1765
01:57:43.556 --> 01:57:45.891
Prepare to pay the price, Chris.

1766
01:57:46.809 --> 01:57:48.935
Your actions were clumsy.

1767
01:57:49.020 --> 01:57:50.687
Full of holes.

1768
01:57:50.813 --> 01:57:53.940
Almost like someone
begging to be found out.

1769
01:57:57.528 --> 01:58:00.447
It would be fitting
if I were apprehended

1770
01:58:00.531 --> 01:58:02.449
and punished.

1771
01:58:03.576 --> 01:58:07.329
At least there would be
some small sign of justice.

1772
01:58:07.330 --> 01:58:10.332
Some small...

1773
01:58:11.042 --> 01:58:14.461
...measure of hope
for the possibility of meaning.

1774
01:58:16.839 --> 01:58:20.050
Chris Wilton killed them.
I see how he did it.

1775
01:58:20.093 --> 01:58:21.843
What?

1776
01:58:23.096 --> 01:58:24.679
It's as we speculated

1777
01:58:24.722 --> 01:58:27.099
and said was too elaborate,
but that's what he did.

1778
01:58:27.225 --> 01:58:30.310
He killed the next-door neighbor first
to throw us off the scent

1779
01:58:30.353 --> 01:58:32.062
and set up the appearance of a robbery.

1780
01:58:32.105 --> 01:58:33.105
He waited in the hall.

1781
01:58:33.231 --> 01:58:35.107
He knew she'd be back
the same time as usual,

1782
01:58:35.191 --> 01:58:38.443
and he killed her, making it seem like
she surprised a burglar running out.

1783
01:58:38.486 --> 01:58:40.612
He planned it all so he could
make the theater in time

1784
01:58:40.738 --> 01:58:42.989
to strengthen his alibi,
if one became necessary.

1785
01:58:43.074 --> 01:58:45.575
Now, I haven't figured out
the weapon problem,

1786
01:58:45.618 --> 01:58:47.119
and I know it's a lot to ask a jury,

1787
01:58:47.203 --> 01:58:49.371
but the correctness of it
came to me in my sleep

1788
01:58:49.455 --> 01:58:51.206
and I am going to break this case.

1789
01:58:51.249 --> 01:58:53.125
I hate to be the bearer
of bad news, Mike.

1790
01:58:53.209 --> 01:58:54.209
What?

1791
01:58:54.252 --> 01:58:56.211
Not that your dream
isn't of primary interest to a jury.

1792
01:58:56.254 --> 01:58:57.504
What's the bad news?

1793
01:58:57.588 --> 01:59:00.507
There was another shooting
in the area last night, 4am.

1794
01:59:00.591 --> 01:59:03.260
A drug addict killed.
Looks like a drug sale turned nasty.

1795
01:59:03.386 --> 01:59:06.596
What, and he confessed
to killing two women before he died?

1796
01:59:06.639 --> 01:59:08.390
No, he didn't have to.

1797
01:59:08.391 --> 01:59:11.643
The old woman's wedding ring
was right in his pocket.

1798
01:59:12.270 --> 01:59:15.522
- No.
- Name and date engraved right on it.

1799
01:59:16.524 --> 01:59:19.776
- I don't believe it.
- I know. I know.

1800
01:59:19.861 --> 01:59:22.154
Your case looked good, lots of motive.

1801
01:59:22.238 --> 01:59:24.489
But his motive
was pretty strong too. Heroin.

1802
01:59:24.782 --> 01:59:27.159
Junkie with a long string
of convictions.

1803
01:59:27.785 --> 01:59:29.786
Killed by one of his own, no doubt.

1804
01:59:29.912 --> 01:59:31.746
Come on, I'll buy you breakfast.

1805
01:59:31.789 --> 01:59:34.124
You can traumatize me
with the rest of your dreams.

1806
01:59:34.167 --> 01:59:35.625
No, wait.

1807
01:59:35.668 --> 01:59:39.671
What if Wilton did it, threw the
jewels away, this guy finds them?

1808
01:59:41.048 --> 01:59:44.426
I don't know.
See what tonight's dream tells you.

1809
01:59:44.510 --> 01:59:47.262
I'm sure a jury will be interested.

1810
01:59:47.305 --> 01:59:49.181
Come on.

1811
01:59:50.516 --> 01:59:51.766
I give up.

1812
01:59:51.809 --> 01:59:53.643
I knew Wilton didn't do it.

1813
01:59:53.686 --> 01:59:56.062
He's another poor schmuck
who cheated on his wife.

1814
01:59:56.147 --> 01:59:59.441
When you see those pictures
of Nola Rice, you can see why though.

1815
02:00:00.151 --> 02:00:02.944
What a world. Am I right?

1816
02:00:03.404 --> 02:00:06.406
Careful, careful.
I'm always afraid they'll drop.

1817
02:00:06.449 --> 02:00:09.451
- Oh, chill out, Dad.
- Babies are so, so soft.

1818
02:00:09.535 --> 02:00:11.453
Right. Champagne.

1819
02:00:11.537 --> 02:00:13.788
- I think he's got your eyes, Chloe.
- Really?

1820
02:00:13.831 --> 02:00:16.208
I think he's got
your coloring darling, I really do.

1821
02:00:16.292 --> 02:00:19.544
Mummy, you can't tell anything yet.
They change all the time.

1822
02:00:20.838 --> 02:00:22.464
- My nephew.
- Uncle, Uncle Tom.

1823
02:00:22.465 --> 02:00:25.175
- Oh, look at these flowers.
- No, he does look like Christopher.

1824
02:00:25.218 --> 02:00:28.720
Actually, speaking of which, didn't you
move into Alan Sinclair's old office?

1825
02:00:28.846 --> 02:00:31.181
- You lucky swine.
- Oh, Mummy, look, he's dreaming.

1826
02:00:31.224 --> 02:00:32.724
Let's work on number two. Come on.

1827
02:00:32.850 --> 02:00:36.186
Come on, he is a handsome boy.
Look at that face.

1828
02:00:36.229 --> 02:00:37.479
Yeah, he's gorgeous.

1829
02:00:37.563 --> 02:00:39.606
Right, here we are. Eleanor. Please...

1830
02:00:39.690 --> 02:00:40.982
- Chloe...
- Good stuff, Papa.

1831
02:00:41.108 --> 02:00:42.609
- Thank you, darling. There you are.
- There we go.

1832
02:00:42.693 --> 02:00:44.819
- It's all right, you stay there.
- I'll pass them round, shall I?

1833
02:00:44.862 --> 02:00:45.862
Please do.

1834
02:00:45.988 --> 02:00:46.988
- What a good idea.
- Darling, have one.

1835
02:00:47.114 --> 02:00:49.324
- To Terence Elliot Wilton.
- Yes.

1836
02:00:49.367 --> 02:00:51.826
With parents like Chloe and Chris,

1837
02:00:51.869 --> 02:00:54.621
this child will be great
at anything he sets his mind to.

1838
02:00:54.747 --> 02:00:56.248
- Thank you, Mummy.
- He will. He...

1839
02:00:56.374 --> 02:00:58.250
Do you know what,
I don't care if he's great.

1840
02:00:58.376 --> 02:00:59.709
I just hope that he's lucky.

1841
02:00:59.752 --> 02:01:01.378
- Oh, lovely.
- What a lovely thought.

1842
02:01:01.462 --> 02:01:02.754
- He probably will be.
- Absolutely adorable.

1843
02:01:02.880 --> 02:01:04.714
- Mummy, are you sure I'm allowed this?
- Yes, yes.

1844
02:01:04.757 --> 02:01:07.592
- Yes, of course you are.
- You haven't had any for months.

1845
02:01:07.635 --> 02:01:09.010
I'd get it down you now, while you can.

1846
02:01:09.136 --> 02:01:10.387
Isn't he handsome?
My God, he's handsome.

1847
02:01:10.513 --> 02:01:12.639
Bet you any money
the next one's a girl.

1848
02:01:14.767 --> 02:01:16.226
What are you saying about him?

1849
02:01:16.269 --> 02:01:18.270
I was just saying he's got
the most adorable cheeks.

1850
02:01:18.396 --> 02:01:22.357
We were just saying how handsome he is.
Just so extraordinarily handsome.

1851
02:01:22.400 --> 02:01:23.650
I wonder what he's thinking.

1852
02:01:23.734 --> 02:01:25.026
Well, you know, they said
he was a thinker. The nurses.

1853
02:01:25.027 --> 02:01:26.736
- Deep thoughts. Deep thoughts.
- Here we are.

1854
02:01:26.779 --> 02:01:28.738
- To Terence.
- To Terence.

1855
02:01:28.781 --> 02:01:31.491
- To Terence.
- And all that sail on him.